CN CHAPTER 2

📡 Digital Communication Notes 📡

1. Parallel vs. Serial Communication

Parallel Communication

  • Definition: Transmits multiple bits simultaneously across multiple channels (e.g., 8 bits at once).
  • Keywords: Speed 🚀, Data Skew, Short-Distance.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Internal Computer Buses (e.g., PCI Express for GPU connections 🎮).
    • Printer Ports (LPT ports for fast data transfer to printers 🖨️).
  • Advantages:
    • High Speed: Ideal for short-distance communication (e.g., RAM ↔︎ CPU).
    • Simple Programming: No need for bit sequencing.
  • Disadvantages:
    • Data Skew: Longer cables cause timing issues (e.g., bits arrive out of order ❌).
    • Costly: Requires multiple wires.

Serial Communication

  • Definition: Sends data one bit at a time over a single channel.
  • Keywords: Sequential 🔄, Reliability, Long-Distance.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • USB 3.0 (high-speed data transfer for external drives 💾).
    • Ethernet Cables (Cat6 for stable internet 🌐).
  • Advantages:
    • Cost-Effective: Fewer wires = cheaper for long distances (e.g., undersea cables 🌊).
    • Less Interference: Single channel reduces crosstalk.
  • Disadvantages:
    • Slower for Short Distances: Latency due to sequential transmission.

2. Synchronous vs. Asynchronous Transmission

Synchronous Transmission

  • Definition: Data sent in fixed-size blocks with shared clock signals ⏱️.
  • Keywords: Full-Duplex, No Gaps, Frames.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Live Streaming (Netflix/YouTube 📺: continuous data flow).
    • SPI Protocol (used in Arduino sensors 🌡️).
  • Advantages:
    • High Efficiency: No start/stop bits → more data per frame.
  • Disadvantages:
    • Clock Synchronization Required: Complex setup.

Asynchronous Transmission

  • Definition: Data sent in variable-sized packets with start/stop bits 🛑.
  • Keywords: Flexibility, Overhead, UART.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Keyboard Input (typing on a PC ⌨️).
    • HTTP Requests (web browsing 🌍).
  • Advantages:
    • No Shared Clock: Devices can have different speeds (e.g., GPS modules 🛰️).
  • Disadvantages:
    • Overhead Bits: 20-30% of bandwidth wasted on control bits.

3. Modes of Communication

Simplex Mode

  • Definition: One-way communication (send OR receive).
  • Keywords: Unidirectional, No Feedback.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • FM Radio 📻 (station → listeners; no reverse).
    • Temperature Sensors 🌡️ (sensor → display unit).
  • Advantage: Full bandwidth for one direction.

Half-Duplex Mode

  • Definition: Two-way but not simultaneous 🔄.
  • Keywords: Walkie-Talkie, Push-to-Talk.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Air Traffic Control 🛩️ (pilot ↔︎ tower; one speaks at a time).
    • Zigbee Networks (smart home devices 🏠).
  • Disadvantage: Collision Risk if both transmit (e.g., walkie-talkie chaos 📢).

Full-Duplex Mode

  • Definition: Simultaneous two-way communication 🗣️👂.
  • Keywords: Telephone, VoIP, Duplex Channels.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Zoom Calls 🎥 (talk and listen while sharing screen).
    • 4G/5G Networks 📱 (download & upload simultaneously).
  • Advantage: Zero Delay in bidirectional communication.

4. Multiplexing Techniques

Frequency-Division Multiplexing (FDM)

  • Definition: Divides bandwidth into frequency bands 📶.
  • Keywords: Analog Signals, Radio Stations.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Cable TV 📺 (multiple channels on one cable).
    • Wi-Fi Channels (2.4 GHz vs. 5 GHz bands 📡).
  • Disadvantages:
    • Crosstalk: Overlapping frequencies cause noise (e.g., old FM radios 🔇).

Time-Division Multiplexing (TDM)

  • Definition: Allocates time slots to users 🕒.
  • Keywords: Digital Signals, Efficiency.
  • Types:
    • Synchronous TDM: Fixed slots (e.g., T1 Lines for offices 🏢).
    • Asynchronous TDM: Dynamic slots (e.g., Internet Packets 🌐).
  • Real-Life Example:
    • 4G LTE Networks 📶 (multiple users share the same frequency).

Wavelength-Division Multiplexing (WDM)

  • Definition: Uses different light wavelengths in fiber optics 🌈.
  • Real-Life Example:
    • Submarine Internet Cables 🌊 (terabits of data via light pulses).

5. Communication Media

Guided Media

  1. Twisted Pair Cable:
    • UTP: Unshielded (Cat6 for offices 🏢; 1 Gbps speed).
    • STP: Shielded (industrial robots 🤖; reduces EMI).
  2. Coaxial Cable:
    • Types:
      • Baseband (single signal; e.g., CCTV cameras 🎥).
      • Broadband (multiple signals; e.g., cable internet 📶).
  3. Fiber Optic:
    • Single-Mode: Long-distance (e.g., intercity networks 🌆).
    • Multi-Mode: Short-distance (e.g., LANs 🏠).

Unguided Media

  1. Radio Waves:
    • Applications:
      • Bluetooth 🎧 (short-range).
      • Satellite TV 📡 (geostationary satellites).
  2. Infrared:
    • Example: TV Remotes 📺 (line-of-sight required 🔦).
    • Limitation: Sunlight interferes outdoors ☀️.
  3. Microwaves:
    • Example: Radar Systems 🚁 (air traffic control).

6. Switching Techniques

Circuit Switching

  • Phases:
    1. Establishment (dialing a number ☎️).
    2. Data Transfer (voice call 🗣️).
    3. Termination (hanging up 📴).
  • Real-Life Example: Traditional Landlines (dedicated path for entire call).
  • Disadvantage: Inefficient Bandwidth (e.g., silent gaps in calls 🤫).

Message Switching

  • Definition: Store-and-Forward entire messages ✉️.
  • Real-Life Example: Old Email Systems (messages routed via servers 📨).
  • Advantage: Traffic Management (prioritize critical messages 🚨).

Packet Switching

  • Types:
    • Datagram: Independent packets (e.g., IP Networks 🌐).
    • Virtual Circuit: Predefined path (e.g., ATM Networks 💳).
  • Real-Life Example: Streaming Netflix 🎬 (packets take varied paths for speed).
  • Advantage: Fault Tolerance (if one path fails, use another 🛠️).
